body:
Playground link: https://play.rust-lang.org/?version=stable&mode=debug&edition=2018&gist=efbde4267fa53c01fd24ee88c52727c9

Essentially, here's my contrived example:
```rust
pub trait Test {
    type Test;
    fn test(self) -> Self::Test where Self: Sized;
}

impl Test for [u8; 0] {
    type Test = ();
    fn test(self) -> Self::Test {}
}

impl Test for [u8] {
    type Test = ();
    fn test(self) -> Self::Test {}
}
```

Whether you include or remove the `Test::test` method for `[u8]`, this refuses to compile, as `[u8]: !Sized`.

I'm not sure if this is intentional or not, but considering how adding `where Self: Sized` to optional methods works fine, I find this at least surprising. I'm not sure whether this should be changed into a diagnostic which states that this kind of thing is explicitly forbidden for required methods, or if omitting the method should be allowed.

My main goal is to require a by-value method for sized types, but to not require it for unsized types and settle for just by-ref methods.
